#!perl

=head1 NAME

lilith - Forward EVE log alerts to Postgresql as well as make it searchable.

=head1 SYNOPSIS

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> run

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> class_map

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> dump_self

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> event [B<-t> <table>] B<--id> <row_id> [B<--raw>]
[[B<--pcap> <output file>] [B<--virani> <remote>] [B<--buffer> <buffer secodns>]]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> event [B<-t> <table>] B<--event> <event_id> [B<--raw>]
[[B<--pcap> <output file>] [B<--virani> <remote>] [B<--buffer> <buffer secodns>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> extend [B<-Z>] [B<-m> <minutes>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> get_short_class_snmp_list

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> search [B<--output> <return>] [B<-t> <table>]
[B<-m> <minutes>] [B<--order> <clm>] [B<--limit> <int>] [B<--offset> <int>]
[B<--orderdir> <dir>] [B<--si> <src_ip>] [B<--di> <<dst_ip>] [B<--ip> <ip>]
[B<--sp> <<src_port>] [B<--dp> <<dst_port>] [B<--port> <<port>] [B<--host> <host>]
[B<--ih> <host>] [B<-i> <instance>] [B<-c> <class>] [B<-s> <sig>] [B<--if> <if>]subaction
[B<--ap> <proto>] [B<--gid> <gid>] [B<--sid> <sid>] [B<--rev> <rev>]
[B<--subip> <subip>] [B<--subhost> <subhost>] [B<--slug> <slug>] [B<--pkg> <pkg>]
[B<--malscore> <malscore>] [B<--size> <size>] [B<--target> <target>]
[B<--task> <task>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc [B<-t> <table>] B<--id> <row_id> B<--to> <targets>
[B<--note> <note>] [B<--by> <who>] [B<--output> <return>] [B<--pretty>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_history [B<-t> <table>] B<--id> <row_id>
[B<--output> <return>] [B<--raw>] [B<--pretty>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_types [B<--output> <return>] [B<--pretty>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_targets [B<--output> <return>] [B<--pretty>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_target_get <B<--tid> <id>|B<--name> <name>> [B<--pretty>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_target_create B<--name> <name> B<--type> <type>
[B<--set> <key=value>] [B<--desc> <desc>] [B<--disable>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_target_update <B<--tid> <id>|B<--name> <name>>
[B<--set> <key=value>] [B<--desc> <desc>] [B<--enable>] [B<--disable>]

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_target_delete <B<--tid> <id>|B<--name> <name>>

lilith [B<-c> <config>] B<-a> esc_target_test <B<--tid> <id>|B<--name> <name>> [B<--pretty>]

=head1 DESCRIPTION

This script runs various actions for Lilith, including search and the daemon.

=head1 GENERAL SWITCHES

=head2 -a <action>

The action to perform.

    - Default :: search

=head2 -c <config>

The config file to use.

    - Default :: /usr/local/etc/lilith.toml

=head2 -t <table>

Table to operate on.

    - Default :: suricata

=head1 ACTIONS

=head2 run

Start processing the EVE logs and daemonize.

=head2 class_map

Print a table of class mapping from long name to the short name used for display in the search results.


=head2 dump_self

Initiate Lilith and then dump it via Data::Dumper.

=head2 event

Fetches a event. The table to use can be specified via -t.

=head3 --id <row_id>

Fetch event via row ID.

=head3 --event <event_id>

Fetch the event via the event ID.

=head2 --raw

Do not decode the EVE JSON.

=head3 --pcap <file>

Fetch the remote PCAP via Virani and write it to the file. Only usable for with Suricata tables.

Default :: undef

=head3 --virani <conf>

Virani setting to pass to -r.

Default :: instance name in alert

=head3 --buffer <secs>

How many seconds to pad the start and end time with.

Default :: 60


=head2 extend

Prints a LibreNMS style extend.

=head3 -Z

Enable Gzip+Base64 LibreNMS style extend compression.

=head3 -m <minutes>

How far back to search. For the extend action, 5 minutes
is the default.

=head3 -d <dir>

The directory to write it out too.

=head2 get_short_class_snmp_list

Print a list of shorted class names for use with SNMP.

=head2 search

Search the DB. The table may be specified via -t.

The common option types for search are as below.

    - Integer :: A comma seperated list of integers to check for. Any number
                 prefixed with a ! will be negated.
    - String :: A string to check for. May be matched using like or negated via
                the proper options.
    - Complex :: A item to match.
    - IP :: An IP.

=head3 General Search Options

=head4 --output <return>

The output type.

    - Values :: table,json
    - Default :: table

=head4 -m <minute>

How far back to to in minutes.

    - Default :: 1440

    - Default, extend :: 5

=head4 --order <column>

Column to use for sorting by.

    - Default :: timestamp

    - Cape Default :: stop

=head4 --orderdir <direction>

Direction to order in.

    - Values :: ASC,DSC
    - Default :: ASC

=head3 IP Options

=head4 --si <src IP>

Source IP.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: IP

=head4  --di <dst IP>

Destination IP.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: IP

=head4  --ip <IP>

IP, either dst or src.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: complex IP

=head3  Port Options

=head4 --sp <src port>

Source port.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4  --dp <dst port>

Destination port.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4 -p <port>

Port, either dst or src.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: complex integer

=head3 Host Options

    Sagan :: Host is the sending system and instance host is the host the
             instance is running on.

    Suricata :: Host is the system the instance is running on. There is no
                instance host.

=head4 --host <host>

Host.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 Instance Options

=head4 --ih <host>

Instance host.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 Instance Options

=head4 -i  <instance>

Instance.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 Class Options

=head4 -c <class>

Classification. May be specified multiple times or as a comma
separated list to search for more than one. Positive items are
ORed together while items negated via a leading '!' are ANDed.

    # class = 'Misc Attack'
    -c 'Misc Attack'

    # class in ( 'Misc Attack', 'Exploit Attempt' )
    -c 'Misc Attack' -c 'Exploit Attempt'
    -c 'Misc Attack,Exploit Attempt'

    # class != 'Misc activity' and class not like 'Generic%'
    -c '!Misc activity' -c '!Generic%'

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 Signature Options

=head4 -s <sig>

Signature.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 In Interface Options

=head4 --if <if>

Interface.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 App Proto Options

=head4 --ap <proto>

App proto.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head3 Rule Options

=head4 --gid <gid>

GID.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4 --sid <sid>

SID.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4 --rev <rev>

Rev.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head3 CAPEv2 Options

=head4 --slug <slug>

The slug it was submitted with.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string


=head4 --pkg <pkg>

The detopnation package used with CAPEv2.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head4 --malscore <malscore>

The malscore of the sample.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4 --size <size>

The size of the sample.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4 --target <target>

The the detonation target.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head4 --task <task>

The task ID of the run.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: integer

=head4 --subip <subip>

The IP the sample was submitted from.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: IP

=head4 --subhost <subhost>

The host the sample was submitted from.

    - Default :: undef
    - Type :: string

=head2 esc

Escalates a event to one or more escalation targets. The table is picked
via -t and the event via --id. Every attempt is recorded in the
escalations table and the event's escalations array. Exits non-zero if
any target failed.

=head3 --id <row_id>

The row ID of the event to escalate.

=head3 --to <targets>

Comma separated list of escalation targets to escalate to. Each item may
be either a target ID or a target name.

=head3 --note <note>

A optional note to record with the escalation.

    - Default :: undef

=head3 --by <who>

Who requested the escalation, recorded as requested_by.

    - Default :: the current user

=head3 --output <return>

The output format, either table or json.

    - Default :: table

=head2 esc_history

Prints the escalations recorded for a event, newest first. The table is
picked via -t and the event via --id. With --output json the raw payload
of each escalation is included, decoded unless --raw is given.

=head2 esc_types

Lists the available escalation types along with the config fields each
one takes, for use with --set. --output json prints the full type info.

=head2 esc_targets

Lists the configured escalation targets. --output json includes the
config of each.

=head2 esc_target_get

Prints a single escalation target as JSON, including its config. The
target is picked via --tid or --name.

=head3 --tid <id>

The escalation target ID.

=head3 --name <name>

The escalation target name.

=head2 esc_target_create

Creates a new escalation target and prints its ID.

=head3 --name <name>

The name for the new target. Required.

=head3 --type <type>

The escalation type, as listed by esc_types. Required.

=head3 --set <key=value>

A config item for the type. May be given multiple times. The keys a type
takes are listed by esc_types.

=head3 --desc <desc>

A optional description.

=head3 --disable

Create the target disabled.

=head2 esc_target_update

Updates a escalation target, picked via --tid or --name. Only the items
specified change. --set items are merged over the current config; a
empty value, e.g. --set apikey=, removes that key so the type default
applies. When the target is picked via --tid, --name renames it.

=head3 --enable

Enable the target.

=head3 --disable

Disable the target.

=head2 esc_target_delete

Deletes a escalation target, picked via --tid or --name. Escalations
recorded to it are kept, with the name they were recorded under.

=head2 esc_target_test

Sends a synthetic test event to a escalation target, picked via --tid or
--name, and prints the payload sent as JSON.

=head2 auto_escalate

Evaluates the enabled auto escalation rules against recently ingested
alerts and escalates each match to the rule's targets. Meant to be run
periodically (cron/timer). Prints a per-table summary as a table, or as
JSON with C<--output json>.

=head3 --tables <list>

Comma separated list of alert tables to scan (suricata/sagan/cape). All
three are scanned when not given.

=head3 -m <minutes>

How far back to look for alerts that have not yet been considered.

    - Default :: 5

=head3 --dry-run

Evaluate rules and report what would be escalated, without sending
anything or marking any alert as considered.

=head3 --by <who>

Recorded (prefixed onto the rule name) as the requester of each
escalation.

    - Default :: auto

=head2 ae_list

Lists the auto escalation rules.

=head2 ae_get

Prints a single auto escalation rule as JSON, picked via --id.

=head2 ae_create

Creates a auto escalation rule. Takes --name, --rule, and optionally
--tables, --priority, --stop, --desc, and --disable.

=head3 --rule <json>

The rule as a JSON object, or C<@file> to read the JSON from a file. See
L<Lilith::AutoEscalate> for the match/actions format.

=head3 --tables <list>

Comma separated alert tables the rule applies to. All three when not
given.

=head3 --priority <int>

Evaluation order, lower first.

    - Default :: 100

=head3 --stop

Set stop_on_match so later rules do not fire on a alert this rule
matched.

=head2 ae_update

Updates a auto escalation rule, picked via --id. Any of --name, --rule,
--tables, --priority, --stop, --desc, --enable, or --disable may be
given.

=head2 ae_delete

Deletes a auto escalation rule, picked via --id.

=head1 ENVIROMENTAL VARIABLES

=head2 Lilith_color_enable

Set to enable colorized output.

    - Default :: 0

=head2 Lilith_table_color

The L<Text::ANSITable> table color to use.

    - Default :: Text::ANSITable::Standard::NoGradation

=head2 Lilith_table_border

The L<Text::ANSITable> border type to use.

    - Default :: ASCII::None

=head2 Lilith_IP_color

Perl boolean for if IPs should be colored or not.

    - Default :: 1

=head2 Lilith_IP_private_color

ANSI color to use for private IPs.

    - Default :: bright_green

=head2 Lilith_IP_remote_color

ANSI color to use for remote IPs.

    - Default :: bright_yellow

=head2 Lilith_IP_local_color

ANSI color to use for local IPs.

    - Default :: bright_red

=head2 Lilith_timesamp_drop_micro

Perl boolean for if microseconds should be dropped or not.

    - Default :: 1

=head2 Lilith_instance_color

If the lilith instance colomn info should be colored.

    - Default :: 1

=head2 Lilith_instance_type_color

Color for the instance name.

    - Default :: bright_blue

=head2 Lilith_instance_slug_color

Color for the insance slug.

    - Default :: bright_magenta

=head2 Lilith_instance_loc_color

Color for the insance loc.

    - Default :: bright_cyan.

=head1 CONFIG FILE

The default config file is `/usr/local/etc/lilith.toml`.

    - dsn ::  A DSN connection string to be used by DBI

    - pass :: Password to use for the connection.

    - user :: User to use for the connetion.

    - class_ignore :: Array of classes to ignore.

EVE instances to follow are defined as sub tables under the C<eves> table, i.e.
C<[eves.NAME]>. Each such sub hash is an instance with the following values.

    - eve :: The EVE file to follow.

    - type :: `sagan` or `suricata`, depending on which it is.

    - instance :: The name for the instance. If not specified the sub table name is used.

Example...

    dsn="dbi:Pg:dbname=lilith;host=192.168.1.2"
    pass="WhateverYouSetAsApassword"
    user="lilith"
    # a handy one to ignore for the extend as it is spammy
    class_ignore=["Generic Protocol Command Decode"]

    # add a suricata instance to monitor
    [eves.suricata-eve]
    instance="foo-pie"
    type="suricata"
    eve="/var/log/suricata/alert.json"

    # add a second suricata instance to monitor
    [eves.another-eve]
    instance="foo2-pie"
    type="suricata"
    eve="/var/log/suricata/alert2.json"

    # add a sagan eve to monitor
    # instance name is 'foo-lae', given there is no value for instance
    [eves.foo-lae]
    type="sagan"
    eve="/var/log/sagan/alert.json"

Prior to this the instances were defined as plain top-level tables (e.g.
C<[suricata-eve]>); such tables are now ignored, with a warning suggesting the
C<[eves.NAME]> form.

=cut

